article.description: Texas Tech knew it would take tough defense and strong rebounding to handle Rutgers in the championship game of the women's Preseason NIT.
article.headline: Lady Raiders (4-0) hold another foe under 50
article.linkText: Texas Tech toughs it out for WNIT title
article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Texas Tech knew it would take tough
defense and strong rebounding to handle Rutgers in the championship
game of the women's Preseason NIT.

The Lady Raiders (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) had plenty of both and easily
defeated the 15th-ranked Scarlet Knights 73-45 on Sunday.

"We knew we were going to have to do a great job on the
boards," said Casey Jackson, who led Tech with 10 points and 19
rebounds.

"Coach [Marsha] Sharp told us before the game that there would
be plenty of rebounds available, so we went out and crashed the
boards hard," she said. "As for me, I was just in the right place
at the right time."

The Lady Raiders (4-0) held their fourth consecutive opponent
under 50 points and ran away from their second straight Top 25
rival. Tech defeated Cal Santa Barbara 68-41 Friday night.

Tournament MVP Jia Perkins led Tech in scoring with 15 points.

"I think as a team we're just clicking right now," said
Perkins. "We have a lot of people on this team who can score, and
our defense just keeps getting better. We're playing good team
defense, and we're rebounding well. It's all just coming together
for us."

Texas Tech led 33-21 at halftime, then held Rutgers to eight
points in the first 8:30 of the second half en route to a 49-29
lead.

The Scarlet Knights got no closer than 16 points the rest of the
way. Rutgers was led by Cappie Pondexter with 15 points. Michelle
Campbell added 11 and Dawn McCullouch had 10.

"We were tentative in the post, and we had some early fouls
that put us on our heels," said Pondexter. "I don't think we ever
adjusted from that."

Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said her team played
tentatively.

"I'm not happy about it at all because we're capable of
representing ourselves better than we did in this game," she said.

In the first half, the Lady Raiders scored on 10 of 11
possessions to build a 22-11 lead at the 9:03 mark.

Rutgers (3-1) scored six straight to pull within 22-17 on an
inside basket by Pondexter with 7:11 left in the half, but a
3-pointer by Brooke Baughman with 6:52 left ended the run and gave
Tech breathing room.

"We still have a lot of things we need to work on," said
Sharp. "But I thought we really did a great job of improving
during this tournament. We were really better the last two games at
getting a body on someone and keeping them away from the boards."

Tech outrebounded Rutgers 50-33.
